# Managing Schema migrations with Alembic

## Intro

During this project Alembic will be used to manage different the versions of our database schema, the scope of this document is to quickly describe the process that was followed to setup alembic for the project and how alembic will be used through the rest of the project. 

## Initial setup and file structure

The initial setup of Alembic is already done, the following is a quick description of the process and which files are generated:
1. The first step is to install alembic into a virtual environment (it's already added to ```requirements.txt```)
2. Next the initial setup is carried out by executing ```alembic init alembic``` from ```/path_to_cloned_git_repo/newsradar/backend/app```. This will generate a new directory ```alembic``` with the following structure: 

```
app/
 ├── alembic/
 │   ├── versions/
 │   ├── env.py
 │   └── script.py.mako
 ├── api/
 ├── core/
 ├── modules/
 ├── tests/
 ├── tests/
 ├── alembic.ini
 ...
```

- versions -> where future schema migration scripts will be generated and executed from, they can be modified if needed.
- env.py -> Script python which will indicate Alembic how to interact with the project's database and its tables
- script.py.mako -> A template for the schema migration scripts, all of them will include by default an upgrade() and downgrade() method.
- alembic.ini -> Alembic configuration file, defines several alembic options. For now, only one configuration option was changed from default file: ```sqlalchemy.url = postgresql+psycopg://user:password@localhost:5432/news_db```


## Alembic daily use

Whenever some change has been done to the schema of the database, it's important to autogenerate a new migration script and apply it if possible. This can be achieved with the following commands

**WARNING**: Alembic's migration scripts only handle the schema of the database, therefore problems related to the existing data not being compatible with the new version of the schema may arise when applying upgrades to the database. While in **development**, the easiest way to deal with these problems is to quickly erase the data of the datbase (may be done from the migration script or with ```docker compose down -v``` which will remove all containers and their volumes for a fresh start)

### Autogenerate a migration script

```
alembic revision --autogenerate -m "description"
```

It is important to check the autogenerated migration script to see if Alembic correctly detected the changes that were done to the database

----
### Apply a migration script

```
alembic upgrade head
```
This will go to the last version of the database and will apply all the neccessary migration scripts in the correct order

**NOTE**: Instead of using ```head``` it is possible to use ```+1``` or ```+N``` to upgrade N versions up, this can also be changed by the id of the version (at the start of its migration script)

----
### Revert a migration script

```
alembic downgrade -1
```
This will go down 1 version from the one that is currently applied to the database

----
### Extra commands
----
```
alembic history
```

Will show the history of all the versions of the database

----
```
alembic current
```

Will show the current version of the database